In order to represent a NAND gate in C++, bitwise operators can be used efficiently, utilizing the bitwise NOT (~) operator and the bitwise AND (&) operator. Here's the simplest solution of the problem:

```c++
#include <iostream>

// Function to implement NAND gate
bool NAND(bool a, bool b) {
    return !(a & b);
}

int main() {
    // Test NAND gate function
    std::cout << NAND(0, 0) << std::endl;
    std::cout << NAND(0, 1) << std::endl;
    std::cout << NAND(1, 0) << std::endl;
    std::cout << NAND(1, 1) << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

In the above code first we define a bool function "NAND" which receives two boolean inputs and returns the NAND operation value i.e. "!(a & b)". This can be optimized in terms of CPU cycles.

```c++
#include <iostream>

// Optimized NAND gate - implemented using bitwise NOT (~) and bitwise AND (&)
int NAND(unsigned int a, unsigned int b) {
    return ~a | ~b;
}

int main() {
    // Test NAND gate function
    std::cout << NAND(0, 0) << "\n";
    std::cout << NAND(0, 1) << "\n";
    std::cout << NAND(1, 0) << "\n";
    std::cout << NAND(1, 1) << "\n";

    return 0;
}
```
In optimized code, we converted the boolean type to an int type. All four basic operations (NOT, AND, OR, XOR) can be performed with only one CPU instruction if your data type is an integer. Using "unsigned int" instead of "bool" has the potential to reduce the number of CPU cycles.  Further, by avoiding using "endl", which causes flushing the output buffer, writing to the terminal can be more efficient and we instead use "\n". Please remember to cast the int result back to bool if you need boolean output. This solution is only optimized for modern CPUs that deal with integers in a single cycle, but keep in mind that with different hardware or compiler optimizations, various outputs might be optimal.

The `this` keyword in Java is a reference variable that we use to refer to the current object. More specifically, it holds a reference to the current object, whose method or constructor is being invoked. The `this` keyword can be used to refer to the instance variables of current class, to invoke or initiate current class method/constructor, can be passed as an argument in the method call and can be used to return the current class instance.

Here is a sample program demonstrating different uses of `this` keyword in Java:

```java
class DemoClass {
    int num;

    // A method that receives a number and assigns it to the instance variable
    // Uses "this" to refer to the current class instance variable
    void assignNum(int num) {
        this.num = num; 
        // Without "this", num refers to the method parameter. 
        // So, "this" is necessary to refer to the instance variable
    }

    // A method that prints the square of the instance variable
    // Uses "this" to refer to the current class method
    void printSquare() {
        this.square();
    }

    // A method that squares the instance variable
    // Demonstrates use of "this" to refer to the current class instance variable
    void square() {
        System.out.println(this.num * this.num);
    }

    // A method that returns the current object
    // Uses "this" to return the current class instance
    DemoClass getThis() {
        return this;
    }

    // A method that accepts an instance of DemoClass and prints the "num" variable
    static void printNum(DemoClass obj) {
        System.out.println("Num is " + obj.num);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        DemoClass demo = new DemoClass();
        demo.assignNum(5);
        demo.printSquare(); // prints 25
        printNum(demo.getThis()); // prints Num is 5
    }
}
```

In the absence of "this" keyword, if instance variable and method parameter has the same name then local variables i.e method parameters will get precedence. This would not change the instance variable which would lead to unintended results. For example, in the `assignNum(int num)` method above, without "this", `num` refers to the method parameter, not the instance variable `num`. So, "this" is necessary to refer to the instance variable.

