Here is the improved and debugged function:

```python
from typing import List

def separate_paren_groups(paren_string: str, inner_paren: bool = False) -> List[str]:

    # Preprocess input string to remove spaces
    paren_string = "".join(paren_string.split(" "))
    groups = []

    def parse_paren(start: int, parent_start: bool = False):
        stack = []
        for idx, ch in enumerate(paren_string[start:], start=start):
            if ch in "([{":
                if inner_paren and stack and not parent_start:
                    parse_paren(idx, True)
                stack.append(ch)
            elif ch in ")]}":
                start_char = stack.pop()
                allowed_chars = {'(':')', '[':']', '{':'}'}
                if allowed_chars[start_char] != ch:
                    raise ValueError("Mismatched brackets")
                if not stack:
                    groups.append(paren_string[start:idx+1])
                    break
    parse_paren(0)
    return groups
```
I use a recursive function to handle nested parentheses groups. 

In this function, if "inner_paren" is True and there are already some characters in the stack (which means the new character is in a nested parentheses group), I recursively call the parsing function to handle the nested group. But for the first character of the string and the characters right after a closed group, I don't call the function even if "inner_paren" is True, as they are start-points of top-level parentheses groups.

When I encounter a closing character, I ensure it matches the most recent opening character in the stack and raise an error if they mismatch. Once I matched all the opening characters in the stack, I add the group to the results and stop the parsing for the group.

I start the parsing with the first character of the string. The parsing function will recursively call itself when it encounters nested parentheses groups. 

The time complexity is O(n) since I go through each character exactly once, and the space complexity is also O(n) because of recursion and the string slicing to append results.

A global variable refers to a variable that can be accessed and modified by any part of the program. It is defined outside all functions and is available throughout the life of the program.

Implementing a Singleton class with thread-safe instantiation in C++ can be done as follows:

```C++
#include <mutex>

class Singleton {
private:
    static Singleton* instance;
    static std::mutex mtx;

    // Private constructor so that no objects can be created.
    Singleton() {}

public:

    // Delete copy constructor and assignment operator
    Singleton(const Singleton&) = delete;
    Singleton& operator=(const Singleton&) = delete;

    static Singleton* getInstance() {
        if (instance == nullptr) {
            std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock(mtx);
            if (instance == nullptr) {
                instance = new Singleton();
            }
        }
        return instance;
    }
};

// Initialize static members
Singleton* Singleton::instance = nullptr;
std::mutex Singleton::mtx;

int main()
{
    Singleton* s = Singleton::getInstance();
    return 0;
}
```

In this code, we use a double-checked locking pattern to ensure that the Singleton instance is only created once, even in a multithreaded environment. We do this by first checking if an instance already exists. If it does not, we lock the mutex to prevent other threads from creating an instance at the same time. Then we check again if an instance was created since our last check. If no instance was created, we create one. 

The `std::lock_guard` is a class template that provides a convenient RAII-style mechanism for owning a mutex for the duration of a scoped block.

The copy constructor and the assignment operator are marked as delete to ensure the Singleton instance cannot be copied.

