Here is an approach using two pointers. We move the pointers from the start and end of the array towards the center. When we encounter a pair that is not equal, we replace the one that is not in the subset with the other element if it is in the subset, or replace both with the smallest element in the subset if neither is in the subset. We keep track of how many replacements we make and break the loop when we reach the limit. At the end we make a final pass to check whether all pairs are equal and if not, add to the count of changes.

Here is the corresponding python code:

```
def smallest_change_in_subset(arr, limit, subset):
    subset = set(subset)
    changes = 0

    start, end = 0, len(arr) - 1
    while start < end and changes < limit:
        if arr[start] != arr[end]:
            if arr[start] in subset:
                arr[end] = arr[start]
                changes += 1
            elif arr[end] in subset:
                arr[start] = arr[end]
                changes += 1
            else:
                arr[start] = arr[end] = min(subset)
                changes += 2

        start += 1
        end -= 1

    if changes >= limit:
        return changes

    for i in range(len(arr) // 2):
        if arr[i] != arr[-(i+1)]:
            changes += 1

    return changes
```
Please note that this solution does the best it can within the limit and then report the total number of changes that would be needed after the limit has been reached.

